commit.message: Update for release 1.15.0

Several bugs with parsing hex, bin and oct numbers. (#103)

* Fix a bug: Hexadecimal numbers (type 'x') were not considered numeric internally.

This commit fixes an obvious typo in numeric types constant, where type 'x' (hexadecimal) was mistyped as 'h'.

Fixes case 2 in issue #102 (https://github.com/r1chardj0n3s/parse/issues/102).

* Fix several bugs in "int_convert":

- Allow 'base' argument to be optional;
- Don't override the base if it was already specified (the correct solution to partially-fixed issue #65, see: https://github.com/r1chardj0n3s/parse/issues/65);
- When number sign is present, assume number starts at position 1, not 0 so the base detection logic won't fail on signed numbers (the setup for fixing issue #102: https://github.com/r1chardj0n3s/parse/issues/102, but see the next commit for a complete fix).

* Fix incorrect regex and type conversion call for integer numbers (type 'd').

- Don't specify number base by default when calling "int_convert" to allow it to detect base automatically;
- Add sign specifiers at certain parts of regex, so signed numbers are identified correctly.
Despite the fact that the sign specifiers are actually inserted in regex later in the code for type 'd' and other numeric types, since this regex effectively uses 'or' statements, an additional signs regex will only affect the first expression ('\d{w}'), other expressions should be altered separately.

* Update test_parse.py to actually test the recent bugfixes.

- "test_hex_looks_like_binary_issue65" was merged with "test_numbers", since now it should be considered a separate case;
- Introduced various tests on signed numbers parsing.

fixes #65
fixes #83
fixes #102
